<a href="https://pubads.g.doubleclick.net/gampad/jump?iu=0&sz=1&c=234" target="_blank"><img src="https://pubads.g.doubleclick.net/gampad/ad?iu=0&sz=1&c=234" border="0" alt=""></a> He received a phone call informing him that his brother had died! Speaking to Daily Sun, Molefe said that he went to visit his brother in Soweto yesterday (1 February). When he arrived at his house, he found that nobody was there. Startled, he drove out. On his way home, he received a chilling call from a relative. The message read that David had died. “I was not even aware that he was at hospital,” a shaken Molefe told the People’s Paper. He had been very ill, and it is believed that he died of kidney failure. “I was just going there to check on how he was and I found nobody home. “On my way home, a call came in and I was informed that he passed at 1pm,” he said. David was reportedly taken to Chris Hani Baragwanath Hospital in Soweto on Wednesday (31 January) night. Molefe said that the country had experienced a great loss. “Well, not only the Pheto family experienced loss, but also his friends and the whole country. “He had so much to offer in theatre and education. “It has not settled with me that he’ gone— I’m still shaken.” Molefe described his brother, David, as a generous person. “He was giving to a point where he was abused. “He would go out of his way to do everything for everybody. “You come in with problems, he will find something to help you with,” he said. Details of his memorial service and burial have not yet been released. Phetoe (82) was known for his role as Archie Moroka’s father, Paul Moroka on the popular soapie Generations. He has also acted in movies like Cry, The Beloved Country, Blind Justice, Lethal Ninja, The Fourth Reich, Bush Rink and Dragonard. Phetoe was an actor, director and theatre producer. He was well-known for not only his acts on the small screen but also as a theatre producer